<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lamassoure Denies Wanting Large State Supremacy in EC </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0202170394 Paris AFP in English 1649 GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0202170394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Paris, Feb 2 (AFP) -- French Minister for 
European Affairs Alain Lamassoure denied Wednesday [2 February] 
that he wanted to ensure the supremacy of the larger countries 
in the European Community. 
  In an interview with the regional daily OUEST-FRANCE, 
Lamassoure defended his idea for coordination on policy among 
Germany, France and Spain, which will successively succeed 
Greece in the six-month rotating presidency of the EC from June. 
  "The chances of the calendar mean that the presidency, after 
being held by small and medium countries (Denmark, Belgium and 
Greece), will be taken by three large ones," he said. 
  For that reason "it is necessary to organise ourselves to 
use 
these 18 months in the best way." [passage omitted] 
  Lamassoure said the current system of a rotating presidency 
had the advantage of giving every member an equal share of 
responsibility, but it also did not clearly identify the power 
which should represent Europe out of the Commission of permanent 
officials, the Council of Ministers and the presidency. 
  The French minister said there would be a proposal to remedy 
this in 1996 when EC governments will review the community's 
institutions. 

</TEXT>

