<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Granic Comments on Meeting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0302175894 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1600 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0302175894 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Andjelko Perincic from Rome for </F>
Croatian radio] 
  [Excerpts] Mate Granic, the Croatian deputy prime minister 
and foreign minister held talks with his Italian counterpart, 
Beniamino Andreatta, in Rome this afternoon. They discussed the 
development of bilateral relations and problems in our region. 
[passage omitted] 
  [Begin Granic recording] Concerning the problems in the 
region, we spent most of the time discussing Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
Italy was interested in the accusations of the Croatian Army's 
presence in Bosnia-Herzegovina, which I energetically refuted 
and said that, according to our data, there are about 2,000 
volunteers [from Croatia in Bosnia-Herzegovina] -- some of whom 
were members of the Croatian Army -- but there are no military 
units. Croatia is ready to allow the supervision of borders 
between Bosnia-Herzegovina and Croatia. Of course, the UN 
Security Council has recommended the supervision of all 
Bosnia-Herzegovina's borders. Likewise, Croatia is not planning 
any military action in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  We also discussed future negotiations with the Muslim side. 
In the spirit of the EU's proposal and possible new proposals, 
which are being discussed in the great circles of power, Croatia 
is ready to immediately resume talks with the Muslim side. We 
believe that the talks will soon take place. 
  It is in Croatia's great interest that all conflicts between 
Croats and Muslims should end as soon as possible. Croatia 
believes that a permanent solution to Croatian-Muslim relations 
is the basis for one of the strategic guidelines of Croatia's 
foreign policy. 
  Concerning the joint declaration signed by the Federal 
Republic of Yugoslavia and the Republic of Croatia, it is 
directed exclusively toward the normalization of state relations 
and overall relations between Croats and Serbs, including 
Croatia's priority, which is the reintegration of the UN 
protected areas into Croatia's state and legal system. [end 
recording] [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

