<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   EC, Western Leaders React to Weekend Shellings in Sarajevo </TI></H3>
<H4>   Austria's Mock Endorses Military Action </H4>
<F P=102> AU0702124794 Vienna Oesterreich Eins Radio Network in German 
1100 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0702124794 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna Oesterreich Eins Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone interview with Foreign Minister Alois Mock by </F>
Elisa Wasch; place and date not given -- recorded] 
  [Text] [Mock] [As far as Bosnia-Herzegovina is 
concerned], I think that the point is not to adopt new 
resolutions, most of which have lost credibility, but, finally, 
to set a sign of hope by implementing at least one or more 
resolutions that will have a protective effect for the 
population in certain areas -- if necessary through military 
intervention in specific cases, which has been announced five 
times before but has never been put into practice. 
  [Wasch] Foreign Minister, do you not think that it is easy 
for Austria, which is not a NATO member, to call for air strikes? 
  [Mock] It is not at all easy. What we do is abide by the 
principles of the UN Charter and international law; we have 
always said coercive military action should be the last resort. 
However, if such action is necessary to halt aggression and to 
create, at least, a chance to find a way out of chaos, then one 
can only pursue this course. 
  [Wasch] Do you think NATO will be influenced by Austria's 
demand? 
  [Mock] Certainly not. Nevertheless, we have been asked, and 
I have been invited, to participate in a conference of 
neighboring countries in Geneva. I will stick to our course 
there. If others think that order can be restored by dividing 
up recognized countries, or by rewarding aggression -- then this 
is their opinion with which I will not identify. However, one 
will have to regard that as a most serious warning for 
medium-sized and small countries. One will have to be aware of 
the fact that the law hardly counts in current international 
politics, all that matters is strength. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-38638 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu025aa_94003" </HT>


