<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   German Government Considers `Military Measures' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0602132794 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1234 GMT 6 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0602132794 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DDP/ADN) -- Following the massacre committed 
by the Serb besiegers in Sarajevo, the German Government today 
called on the relevant UN bodies to act on decisions in order to 
prevent those responsible for the massacre from carrying out any 
more violence against the civilian population. "The use of 
targeted military measures, as offered to the United Nations by 
NATO on 9 August 1993, must no longer be ruled out," German 
Government spokesman Dieter Vogel said in Bonn today. 
  The German Government most strongly condemned the bloodbath 
among the civilian population, he said. The brutal attack on 
innocent women, men, and children showed an "incomprehensible 
contempt for human lives on the part of those responsible." The 
German Government expressed its sympathy to the relatives and 
declared its willingness to support U.S. efforts to provide 
medical care for the surviving victims wherever possible. This 
act of violence clearly shows "the urgent need for an immediate 
peace settlement in Bosnia-Hercegovina." 

</TEXT>

