<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Secretary Perry Remarks on Sarajevo, NATO Role </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0602135094 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1245 GMT 6 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0602135094 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Munich (DDP/ADN) -- William Perry, the new U.S. 
secretary of defense, has not ruled out targeted air strikes by 
NATO in the Bosnian civil war areas. Speaking at the 31st 
Conference on Security Policy in Munich, Perry stressed, 
however, that the United States would by no means take such 
steps unilaterally, because 28,000 lightly armed UN soldiers 
stationed in Bosnia, who had been made available by its allies, 
were surrounded by 200,000 "highly armed combatants." 
  NATO had the capacity to carry out such air strikes, Perry 
underlined. It would be possible to begin such a strike only an 
hour after the command was given, because all the means 
necessary to do so had been deployed. Consideration would still 
have to be paid to the probable political consequences of such 
an attack. Thought must be given not just to the first act, but 
also to whom would play the second and third acts and end the 
drama, Perry said. 
  Perry said another available option was to lift the arms 
embargo against Bosnia. On the other hand, he ruled out a 
military enforcement of a peace solution in Bosnia. Perry also 
rejected the view that NATO and the United States were inactive. 
The provision of supplies from the air alone had assumed 
dimensions which were comparable to the Berlin airlift. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-38659 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu025cc_94001" </HT>


