<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kinkel Calls For Croatian Troop To Withdraw From Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0702110394 Hamburg BILD AM SONNTAG in German 6 Feb 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> AU0702110394 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg BILD AM SONNTAG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Guest commentary" by Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel: </F>
"Croatian Troops, Get Out of Bosnia"] 
  [Text] Croatian troops in Bosnia have no business being 
there. This was also noted by the UN Security Council last 
Thursday [3 February]. It threatened measures against Croatia, 
if these troops are not withdrawn. This withdrawal must take 
place. 
  It is not only the Serbs who have violated the cease-fire 
the 
parties to the conflict promised the European Union [EU] foreign 
ministers. Bosnian troops, too, have initiated a major 
offensive against Croat towns in central Bosnia. The senseless 
killing, misery, suffering, and the driving away of people has 
to stop. Bosnian Muslims and Croats need each other. 
  The UN Security Council has given Croatia a period of two 
weeks. It then intends to decide on measures against Croatia, 
which might also entail the danger of further streams of 
refugees to Germany, a radicalization, and endangering 
humanitarian aid. Therefore, we must make good use of the time. 
Therefore, at next Monday's meeting of the 12 EU foreign 
ministers, I will advocate that we Europeans, in close 
cooperation with Croats and Muslims, seek an understanding that 
restores order to the deeply disturbed Croat-Muslim relations. 
This is the key issue. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

