<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   SPD: Military Intervention Would `Worsen Bloodshed' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0602192194 Mainz ZDF Television Network in German 1810 GMT 
6 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0602192194 </F>
<F P=104>  Mainz ZDF Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with SPD Chairman Rudolf Scharping by Peter </F>
Ellgaard in Mainz on 6 February -- recorded] 
  [Excerpt] [Ellgaard] Mr. Scharping, in Munich you said 
there are no real differences with the Federal Government on 
basic foreign policy issues. Does this not mean, however, that 
if you want to take over the government, this would require 
revising the Wiesbaden party congress resolution that rules out 
Bundeswehr operations as combat missions? 
  [Scharping] No, not at all. I also said in Munich that we 
did not give up sovereign rights when we joined the United 
Nations. Therefore, we ourselves decide whether and to what 
extent we participate in UN measures. This is the only central 
difference with the Federal Government. We, the Social 
Democratic Party of Germany [SPD], and a government headed by it 
will not send the Bundeswehr to combat missions anywhere in the 
world. 
  [Ellgaard] If you took over the government, would you 
maintain compulsory military service? After all, this is a 
problem in view of the current thrift measures. 
  [Scharping] Of course. Compulsory military service is a 
very central element for the democratic anchoring of the 
Bundeswehr, and it is part of the political culture in Germany. 
I think that it must remain in existence. 
  [Ellgaard] Mr. Scharping, yesterday's pictures, the massacre 
in Sarajevo, shocked the world. Does the West not finally have 
to make a military intervention now? What is your position? 
  [Scharping] It is the same position as that of the U.S. 
secretary of state. We must step up the pressure, but military 
intervention would worsen the bloodshed rather than stop it. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

