<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chancellor Kohl Addresses Security Conference </TI></H3>
<H4>   Notes West's Role in East Europe </H4>
<F P=102> LD0502114494 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1015 GMT 5 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0502114494 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Munich (DDP/ADN) -- Federal Chancellor Helmut Kohl 
has called on the West to pay closer attention to the social 
effects of the reforms in the countries in East Europe, 
particularly in the states of the former Soviet Union. This was 
one of the most important conclusions to be drawn from the 
election results in Russia, the chancellor said today at a 
conference on security policy in Munich. A further opening of 
western markets to goods from the reformist countries is of 
"strategic importance." More open markets would lead to 
problems and strains, but are ultimately cheaper than "isolation 
and a fortress mentality," the chancellor said. At the same 
time, he called for a more equal distribution of financial 
burdens in the stabilization of economic and social conditions 
in Central and East Europe. Germany has reached the limit of 
its capacity. 
  It was right for the West not to give the Central and East 
European states any unequivocal promises regarding admission, 
Kohl said. This would only have led to new divisions and thus 
new tensions in Europe. The deeply rooted fear of encirclement 
and isolation in Russia must be taken seriously. At the same 
time, Kohl spoke in favor of letting the reformist states know, 
"through quite practical steps" that they are welcome in the 
European Union [EU]. Kohl suggested inviting the government 
heads of these states to an EU summit once a year. 
  Kohl warned against viewing the EU solely as "a glorified 
free trade zone." The Germans in particular need political 
union to prevent relapses into political circumstances like 
those at the beginning of the 20th century. Political union is 
the precondition for peace and freedom in Europe in the 21st 
century, the chancellor underlined. 
  Kohl said it is "indispensable" for Germany to take part in 
"peacekeeping and peacemaking measures" of the international 
community. Not least for this reason, Germany needs a 
Bundeswehr capable of meeting the "new demands" and equipped 
accordingly. This does not mean the militarization of German 
foreign policy. Kohl rejected sending German soldiers to the 
civil war area in former Yugoslavia, however, "in view of recent 
history." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-38672 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu025_h_94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-025 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chancellor Kohl Addresses Security Conference </TI></H3>
<H4>   Defends European Military Defense Role </H4>
<F P=102> LD0502130494 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1132 GMT 5 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0502130494 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Munich (DDP/ADN) -- According to Chancellor Helmut 
Kohl, the German Government intends to adhere to a forces 
strength of 370,000 for the Bundeswehr. This figure "is and 
remains our basic position," Kohl said today at a conference on 
security policy in Munich. The actual Bundeswehr strength will 
average 361,000 during the current year, and probably higher at 
the end of the year. The personnel level of the Bundeswehr had 
fluctuated by 30,000 in previous years, Kohl said. The goal 
must be "to stay around the 370,000 level." 
  Account will be taken of this trend in drawing up the 1994 
budget, Kohl announced. At the same time, he countered 
criticism from the United States that Germany is doing too 
little for military defense. In this context, account also has 
to be taken of the other achievements Germany has contributed to 
European stability. Kohl drew attention to statistics from the 
Canadian Government, according to which: since 1989 Germany has 
provided $341 per capita to support the countries of the former 
Soviet Union, while Canada has provided $67, France $34, Italy 
$31, the United States $30, Japan $5, and Great Britain only $1. 
  Kohl responded with annoyance to reproaches that Germany is 
primarily promoting the dissemination and development of 
chemical weapons. It is "disproportionate" for Germany to be 
cited on every occasion of this kind, while in the shadow of 
this discussion,others are able to continue their deals, the 
chancellor said. In addition, Kohl drew attention to the "time 
bombs" in the form of dangerous nuclear reactors in eastern 
Europe. It is "astonishing" which countries are concluding 
energy supply agreements with the countries where such plants 
are located. Indeed, the "degree of strange calm" with which 
Europe and Japan are accepting these time bombs is generally 
"incomprehensible." 
  Kohl strongly rejected the view that the Russian people are 
"incapable of democracy in the long term." It is "completely 
absurd" to expect Russia to introduce democracy and the market 
economy overnight, Kohl said. If the West denies the Russian 
people these opportunities from the outset, "nothing can come of 
it." The chancellor again called for western markets to be 
opened up to products from eastern Europe. It is a "fairly 
hypocritical policy" to hold out the prospect of involvement in 
NATO, but to cut oneself off from products. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-38673 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu025_h_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-025 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ruehe Notes Bundeswehr `Crisis Reaction Forces' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0502133894 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1230 GMT 5 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0502133894 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Munich (DDP/ADN) -- Defense Minister Volker Ruehe 
has again called for a secure conceptual and financial basis for 
the Bundeswehr. Speaking at a conference on security policy in 
Munich today, Ruehe called for "rapid changes" in financial 
conditions for the troops. At the same time, the defense 
minister announced the establishment of "crisis reaction forces" 
[Krisenreactionskraefte]. 
  The Bundeswehr is in a position to fulfill its mandate with 
regard to domestic defense, he said. However, the troops are 
not yet capable of taking part in measures involving 
"international crisis management." To this end, a flexible, 
adaptable, assertive unit would have to be set up to cover 
missions under UN auspices, Ruehe said. In particular, this 
includes "extensive mobility for the transfer of forces." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

