<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bundeswehr Chief Says Cuts Will Impair Security Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0502153094 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1233 GMT 5 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0502153094 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hamburg (DDP/ADN) -- General Klaus Naumann, the 
Bundeswehr chief of general staff, warns that the latest cuts in 
the defense budget could have far-reaching consequences on the 
Bundeswehr's operational readiness and the scope for action of 
German security policy. In an interview in WELT AM SONNTAG, 
Germany's most senior military officer says "cuts are now being 
made that will lead to parts of the Bundeswehr being unable to 
achieve the degree of operational readiness that its mandate 
demands." 
  It is true that the Defense Ministry is still in the middle 
of the assessment process, but, the general says, its initial 
assessment has been "that we will no longer be able to achieve 
today's level of operational readiness in 1994/95 in many 
sections of the Army." Units will experience staffing 
shortfalls. 

</TEXT>

