<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Intelligence Service To Receive More Tasks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0402151194 Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER RUNDSCHAU in German 
4 Feb 94 p 4 </F>

<F P=103> AU0402151194 </F>
<F P=104>  Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER RUNDSCHAU </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Ferdos Forudastan: "The Federal Intelligence </F>
Service Will Be Granted More Rights"] 
  [Text] Bonn, 3 February -- In the future, the Federal 
Intelligence Service (BND) will not only be responsible for 
intelligence activities, but will also assume tasks in the fight 
against crime as well. The Christian Democratic Union/Christian 
Social Union and Free Democratic Party of Germany [FDP] adopted 
corresponding legal regulations on Thursday [3 February]. Thus, 
they finally settled differences of opinion on the planned "Law 
on the Fight Against Crime 94," which will probably be discussed 
for the first time by the Bundestag on 24 February. 
  The BND should be allowed to pass on findings on weapons and 
drug deals, money laundering, counterfeiting of money, and 
terrorism, obtained accidentally or on purpose, to the police or 
public prosecutor's offices. According to the current 
regulations, the intelligence services are allowed to tap 
telephone conversations abroad only if the "free and democratic 
order" of the FRG or its security are in peril. 
  The coalition has suggested that the satellites and other 
monitoring equipment of the BND should also be used to register 
conversations on a regular basis that include information 
pointing to serious crimes. The BND should also be allowed to 
eavesdrop on persons if prosecution authorities ask for 
administrative assistance in the event of telephone tapping upon 
judicial order. 
  FDP legal expert Burkhard Hirsch and Detlef Kleinert pointed 
out that the coalition's intention is not to expand the tasks of 
the intelligence service. It only wants to "utilize the 
technical possibilities of the BND," Hirsch stressed. He also 
rejected the allegation that the new law is mixing the tasks of 
the secret services and the police. The BND should merely 
"place its equipment at the disposal of the police and provide 
administrative aid." 
  The draft law also stipulates that offenders who are caught 
red-handed should appear in court within one week in the future 
and be kept in prison until that time. Violent crimes should be 
punished more severely. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

