<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage, Official Reaction on Fishing Blockade </TI></H3>
<H4>   Fishermen Blockade Le Havre </H4>
<F P=102> AU0402172094 Paris AFP in English 1638 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0402172094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Le Havre, France, Feb 4 (AFP) -- French 
fishermen blockaded this Channel port Friday [4 February] saying 
that government measures to protect the industry were not enough. 
  Twenty fishing vessels sealed off the major French port, 
immobilising three freighters inside while a ferry from Plymouth 
was forced to wait offshore. 
  Fishing boats from Honfleur across the Seine estuary 
meanwhile blocked the entrance to the river and the inland port 
at Rouen. 
  The Havre fishermen complained they would not get "one cent" 
of aid promised by French Prime Minister Edouard Balladur in 
negotiations Friday with Brittany fishermen in Rennes, the 
Brittany capital. [passage omitted] 
  In the Mediterranean port of Marseille, more than a tonne of 
fish from Algeria and Senegal was held up by health inspectors 
who said the catches did not have the right documents. 
  On Thursday, French authorities ordered stricter checks on 
imported fish as protestors blamed imports for a collapse in 
prices. 

</TEXT>

