<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Education Minister Elected Parliament Speaker </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0702123094 Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network in Finnish 
1100 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0702123094 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Finnish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Education Minister Riitta Uosukainen has been 
elected speaker of the parliament. In an election at a plenum 
in the parliament today, she received 107 votes, while 
Saara-Maria Paakkinen of the Social Democratic Party attracted 
82 votes. In addition, Pentti Maeki-Hakola of the Coalition 
Party got four votes, and Mikko Pesaelae of the Center got one 
vote. Uosukainen became the first ever female chief speaker of 
the parliament. Paakkinen and Pesaelae will continue as deputy 
speakers. 
  With the election of Uosukainen, the Coalition Party will 
carry out a reshuffle within its group of ministers. Under a 
proposal by the parliament group and the party leadership, the 
current Housing Minister Pirjo Rusanen should take over 
Uosukainen's post as education minister. Parliament deputy 
Ritva Laurila, chairman of Helsinki City Council, will become 
new housing minister. The ministerial reshuffle will be 
discussed on 10 February at meetings of the Coalition Party 
Board and parliament group. [passage omitted] 
  President Mauno Koivisto will open the parliamentary session 
of 1994 tomorrow. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

