<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Radio Reports on Sarajevo Shelling </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0602065994 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 0500 GMT 6 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0602065994 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Yesterday was another [word indistinct] day in the 
senseless war in Bosnia-Herzegovina, as 60 persons died 
following a mortar explosion in Sarajevo's central market. 
Another 150 persons were injured, many of whom are in critical 
condition. Bosnia-Herzegovina President Alia Izetbegovic 
accused the Serbs, whereas Radovan Karadzic, leader of the 
Bosnian Serbs attributed the attack to a Muslim provocation in 
order to establish a negative climate against the Serbs. 
  This murderous attack against noncombatants has been 
strongly 
condemned by the United States and other countries. In a 
written statement yesterday, U.S. Secretary of State Warren 
Christopher notes that his country will press for the United 
Nations to specify soon who is responsible for the deadly attack 
in Sarajevo. He also warned that air strikes by NATO should not 
be ruled out once it is determined who is responsible. He 
announced that he had a telephone conversation with his British 
counterpart on the issue and will hold more deliberations with 
other allied countries. 
  The French Foreign Ministry condemned yesterday's massacre 
in 
Sarajevo, saying that France feels horror and disgust. The 
Italian and Belgian foreign ministers asked for specific 
measures in reaction to the attack. 
  In the meantime, talks on ending the hostilities in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina will resume again. The Muslims will finally 
participate in the talks, despite expressing reservations 
yesterday. 
  Lord Owen and Thorvald Stoltenberg, international mediators 
on the Yugoslav dispute announced yesterday that the foreign 
ministers of Greece, Turkey, Albania, Bulgaria, Romania, 
Hungary, Italy, and Austria will meet Wednesday [9 February] in 
Geneva to enforce the peace efforts in Bosnia-Herzegovina. In a 
statement regarding the Geneva meeting, the Greek Foreign 
Ministry notes that the Greek presidency of the European Union 
[EU] intends to examine along with its partners at the EU 
Council of General Affairs meeting, which will take place 
Monday, the reason and usefulness of this meeting at this time. 
According to the statement, Greece will insist on the principle 
that only countries which have borders with the former 
Yugoslavia should participate. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-38702 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu025_p_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-025 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   KKE Cautions Against Air Operation in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0602192894 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1800 GMT 6 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0602192894 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In a statement, the KKE [Greek Communist Party] has 
noted the danger of a general unrest in the Balkans because of 
the planned Western air attack in Bosnia-Herzegovina and has 
called on the government to block any NATO and CSCE decisions in 
this direction. 
  The KKE has asked the country's political powers to clarify 
their position and condemn the manipulated intervention. 

</TEXT>

