<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Velayati Leaves for Istanbul </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402191894 Tehran IRNA in English 1849 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0402191894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Athens, Feb. 4, IRNA -- Iranian Foreign Minister 
'Ali Akbar Velayati left Athens for Istanbul Friday afternoon [4 
February] after ending a brief but hectic 24-hour important 
working visit to Greece. 
  Greek state-run televison channel ET-2 said Velayati's talks 
with Greek Government officials produced "positive results" in 
advancing bilateral realtions. 
  Velayati met and discussed a wide range of issues including 
the situation in Bosnia-Herzegovina and the Middle East with 
Greek Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou, Foreign Minister 
Karolos Papoulias, and parliament President Apostolos Kaklamanis. 
  Papoulias said his talks with Velayati were of "special 
significance" and "they achieved positive results in all 
sectors." 
  Talking to IRNA parliament speaker Kakalmanis noted that "we 
had very friendly talks with the Iranian foreign minister which 
underscores the close ties between our two peoples and 
countries." 
  "I believe that this visit and his talks in Athens will 
contribute in strengthening the excellent relations and 
cooperation," he added. 
  Mass-selling afternoon Greek daily ELEVTHEROTIPIA said 
Velayati's visit "uinderlines the positive climate in 
Greek-Iranian relations, as well as Iran's interests in the 
developments in the Balkans and in promotion of Iran's relations 
with Europe." 
  Greece currently holds the European Union (EU) presidency. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

