<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Comments on Sarajevo Bombing </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0702141794 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1300 
GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0702141794 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Text] Foreign Minister Hikmet Cetin hopes that NATO will 
decide in favor of air raids against the Serbian emplacements in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, adding: Any other decision would only grant 
the Serbians more time to plan new attacks. 
  In a statement prior to his meeting in Ankara with (Enest 
Drakovic), Bosnian minister of education, science, and culture, 
Cetin said that representations have been made with NATO and the 
United Nations following the recent Sarajevo attack in a bid to 
put an end to this barbarism as soon as possible. Cetin said 
the following: 
  [Begin Cetin recording] Our ambassador has been instructed 
to apply to NATO, and the application has been made. Turkey was 
the first to apply to NATO to call the NATO Council to a meeting 
on the issue. Instructions were also given to apply to the UN 
Security Council on the issue of lifting the arms embargo. [end 
recording] 
  In reply to a question, Cetin said that he does not believe 
that UN Secretary General Butrus-Ghali's approval is necessary 
concerning any decision NATO might make regarding intervention. 
  (Drakovic) said that during his contacts he observed that 
Western countries do not want to exert efforts to end this 
massacre. Pointing out that Turkey's continued support 
strengthens the Bosnians, (Drakovic) added that grief caused by 
Saturday's [5 February] attack can be seen on the faces of the 
Turkish people. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

