GMT 6 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0602210094 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Text] Culture Minister Fikri Saglar has said that besides 
an unprecedented genocide in Bosnia-Herzegovina, human culture 
down through centuries is also being destroyed in an act of 
sheer cleansing. Saglar said Turkey is trying to draw the 
attention of the whole world to the savagery of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  (Enest Durakovic), the culture, education, and sports 
minister of Bosnia-Herzegovina [name and title as heard], has 
arrived in Ankara on an official visit. 
  In a statement he issued while receiving the guest minister 
at the airport, Saglar said the countries championing human 
rights and democracy have been displaying indifference in such a 
way as to tolerate massacre and have not been taking the 
necessary measures. Saglar further noted that tomorrow the two 
countries will sign their first cultural protocol as well as 
another protocol on Turkey restoring the historic Mostar bridge 
and other edifices. 
  The guest minister, in turn, asked the whole world to take 
seriously the necessary measures to stop Serbian aggression and 
cruelty. Explaining that in Bosnia-Herzegovina not only are the 
people being eradicated but also a cultural heritage was being 
wiped out, the Bosnian minister stressed that they are 
determined to defend their existence and that Turkey is greatly 
assisting them toward this goal. 

</TEXT>

