<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pope Addresses NATO Officials on Ethnic Conflict </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0802104394 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1547 GMT 7 
Feb 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0802104394 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Pope on War As a Political Choice"] </F>
  [Text] Vatican City, 7 Feb (ANSA) -- The "indescribable 
horrors perpetrated every day against innocent peoples" in 
ex-Yugoslavia were spoken of today by Pope John Paul II as the 
result of old ethnic hatred, "the hatred of one group for 
another" combined with a "series of concrete and determined 
policies." 
  Addressing a group of 150 people attending a seminar 
sponsored by the NATO Defense College in Rome, the pope pointed 
out, "Someone, some time, made some decisions which brought 
terrible consequences of death, offense, destruction and 
mourning." 
  Speaking in English, the pontiff affirmed that the "shocking 
and bloody conflict which is shaking Europe" is making the 
continent less certain of itself and warned that "Europe must 
remember that its destiny cannot depend only on strategic or 
economic interests. It must regain its spirit for the renewal of 
its civil, moral and spiritual life," he added. 
  The ongoing appeals launched by the Holy See and other 
religious leaders and "men of good will," he continued, "are 
directed to the conscience of those who can do something to 
change the course of things. To the present, hope has not been 
compensated," he said before turning to prayer for "you and all 
those who are in the service of the cause of peace." 
  Concluding his remarks, John Paul said, "Peace is a word and 
a desire closed in the hearts of everyone, an essential asset on 
which depends the well-being of the individual and the progress 
of society and civilization." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

