<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Denmark </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll: 44 Percent Oppose Bosnia Air Strikes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0802104094 Paris AFP in English 1009 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0802104094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Copenhagen, Feb 8 (AFP) -- Forty-four percent of 
Danes said they opposed the idea of NATO air strikes in former 
Yugoslavia, while 39 percent supported them and 17 percent had 
no opinion, according to a Gallup poll published Tuesday [8 
February]. 
  The survey, which appeared in the BERLINGSKE TIDENDE daily, 
was made between January 17 and 20 -- before last week's mortar 
attacks that killed civilians in Sarajevo's marketplace and in 
its suburb of Dobrinja -- among more than 1,000 residents. 
  It also showed that 57 percent of Danes want Danish UN 
peacekeepers sent home if the North Atlantic Treaty Organization 
(NATO) starts bombing operations in Bosnia. 
  Another 34 percent felt the soldiers should remain. 
  A majority 59 percent supported Danish participation in 
United Nations peacekeeping operations around the world, while 
32 percent opposed this and nine percent had no opinion. 
  In all 54 percent felt it right that Denmark had sent 
soldiers to former Yugoslavia, while 40 percent felt the 
opposite. 

</TEXT>

