<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Butrus-Ghali Sends Letter to Kliridhis, Denktas </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0602120594 Nicosia CyBC Television Network in Greek 1830 
GMT 5 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0602120594 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia CyBC Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] The Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation [CyBC] 
tonight reveals the contents of UN Secretary General Butrus 
Butrus-Ghali's letter to President Glavkos Kliridhis and Turkish 
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktas, inviting them to proximity talks on 
the confidence-building measures. The letter was handed to the 
two sides today. 
  In his letter, Butrus-Ghali calls on Kliridhis and Denktas 
to 
participate in intense proximity talks in late February to work 
out an agreement on a limited number of significant points 
regarding ways to implement the measures concerning Varosha and 
the Nicosia Airport. 
  The letter mentions that Joe Clark, the UN secretary 
general's special representative in Cyprus, will come to Cyprus 
during the preliminary phase of the talks and Gustave Feissel, 
the UN secretary general's alternate special representative in 
Cyprus, will then take over. The letter adds that Feissel will 
meet Kliridhis and Denktas on Monday [7 February] to determine 
the crucial points. 
  Correspondent Kostandinos Yenaris reports on the letter: 
  [Yenaris] The UN secretary general's letter was handed to 
the 
two sides today in Nicosia, but the contents were not 
publicized. CyBC reveals, however, the full text of the letter, 
in which the UN secretary general says he is satisfied because 
the two sides accepted the confidence-building measures package 
as is. Butrus-Ghali stresses the significance of working out 
ways to implement the measures within two months at the most, so 
as to utilize fully the positive atmosphere that will be created 
when the talks begin. 
  In order to reach an agreement, Butrus-Ghali calls on both 
sides to approach the talks in a constructive spirit, bearing in 
mind the following four points: First, neither side should try 
to secure a political advantage from the talks or demand that 
the other make political concessions. Second, both sides should 
respect fully the confidence-building measures as described in 
the UN secretary general's report. Third, an agreement should 
be fully implemented as soon as it is reached with no delays or 
interventions from either side. Fourth, the goal of the 
measures is to facilitate swift progress toward an overall 
Cyprus solution, not substitute for it. 
  Based on these four points, the UN secretary general calls 
on 
both sides to begin intense negotiations with his 
representatives in Nicosia in late February to reach an 
agreement on a limited number of points regarding ways to 
implement the confidence-building measures. The letter adds 
that Clark will come to Cyprus for the beginning of the talks, 
which will continue with Feissel's participation. Feissel will 
hold talks with the two sides to determine these crucial points. 
[passage omitted] 
  [Announcer] According to CyBC information, despite 
assurances 
by Feissel and Robert Lamb, the U.S. State Department special 
coordinator on the Cyprus issue, that something like this will 
not happen, the Greek Cypriot side expects that during Feissel's 
contacts the Turkish Cypriot side will again attempt to raise 
the issue of redefining the part of Varosha that will be placed 
under UN control. Denktas will insist on not including the 
northern part of the fenced-off area, replacing it with area of 
equivalent size in the south. Our information is that in this 
case, the Greek Cypriot side will not agree to even discuss the 
issue. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

