<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karayalcin: Turkey `Will Reassess' Ties With Allies </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0702201894 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1800 
GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0702201894 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Text] Murat Karayalcin, leader of the Social Democratic 
Populist Party [SDPP], state minister and deputy prime minister, 
has said that Turkey will reassess its relations with its 
allies, depending on the stand they adopt toward the issue of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  In an opening statement at the SDPP Central Executive 
Council 
meeting, Karayalcin said the recent massacre in Sarajevo has 
taken the problem of Bosnia-Herzegovina beyond the dimensions of 
a human tragedy. Stressing that Turkey will not allow the 
problem to be defined as a human tragedy and then discarded 
among the many daily discussions, Karayalcin said that foreign 
policy friendships are different than individual ones. He added: 
  [Begin Karayalcin recording] Should our friends fail to 
demonstrate their friendship after this incident as well, then I 
believe that ties of friendship do not mean a lot. Turkey will 
feel the need to reassess its relations of friendship and mutual 
assistance depending on the stand to be adopted by its allies 
following the developments of 5 February. [end recording] 
  In reply to a question, Karayalcin said Prime Minister Tansu 
Ciller briefed him on the appointment of Isparta Deputy Aykon 
Dogan as state minister. 
  Foreign Minister Hikmet Cetin briefed the meeting on the 
steps taken toward a solution to the Bosnia-Herzegovina problem. 

</TEXT>

