<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   SPD Critical of NATO Air Strikes in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0802090094 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 0721 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0802090094 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Berlin (DDP/ADN) -- Karsten Voigt, the foreign 
policy spokesman of the Social Democratic Party [SPD] group in 
the Bundestag, has expressed scepticism about possible NATO air 
strikes in Bosnia. The consequences of such an air operation 
would have to be considered beforehand, Voigt said today on the 
radio station Radio Brandenburg. Artillery positions around 
Sarajevo could certainly be hit in an attack. However, civilian 
casualties might also be expected, the SPD politician said. 
Following a possible successful operation in Sarajevo, there 
would also be demands for the same to be done in other encircled 
towns in Bosnia. This might lead to an escalation, the 
consequences of which would be incalculable, Voigt stated. 
  SPD defense expert Manfred Opel has also criticized NATO and 
UN plans to intervene in the Bosnian war using air strikes. 
Speaking on Norddeutscher Rundfunk today, Opel described these 
ideas as "political actionism." It is to be feared that the war 
in the Balkans will escalate if such attacks go ahead. NATO 
would become a belligerent, but not one which could intervene 
decisively, he asserted. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

