<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kliridhis Confers With UN's Feissel on Varosha </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0702182494 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1700 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0702182494 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Government will raise the issue of accession to 
the fenced area of Varosha at the proximity talks that are 
expected to open in Cyprus in the middle of next week. 
Government spokesman Ioannis Kasoulidhis said this demand will 
be included in the points that our side will outline on the 
issues to be discussed at the proximity talks. Mr. Kasoulidhis 
made the statement this afternoon after the meeting between 
President Glavkos Kliridhis and UN official Gustave Feissel and 
added that our side will submit a list of points which will 
cover all the aspects of the confidence-building measures. 
  Mr. Feissel said after the meeting that he has not received 
from President Kliridhis or from Rauf Denktas any list of such 
points and expressed the hope that the clarification of these 
points would be completed by the end of this week. Feissel also 
noted: During his contacts, he will make efforts to foster 
understanding and, in a wider sense, agreement between the two 
leaders on the issues to be discussed. Mr. Feissel ruled out 
redefining the Varosha area which will be placed under UN 
control, and he denied reports that repairs have begun at 
Nicosia Airport. 
  Mr. Feissel met with Rauf Denktas at noon today. He will 
have a new meeting with Denktas on Wednesday [9 February], and 
on Thursday he will meet again with President Kliridhis. The 
proximity talks will be held under Joe Clark, who is expected in 
Cyprus on Saturday. 

</TEXT>

