<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Alternate Foreign Minister `Indignant' on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0702133394 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1230 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC0702133394 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] We are indignant. The time has come to apportion 
blame, Greek Alternate Foreign Minister Theodhoros Pangalos said 
this morning as he arrived at the entrance of the building where 
the European Union [EU] Council of Foreign Ministers will meet 
today. 
  Our correspondent in Brussels Nikolaos Bellos reports that 
discussion of the tragedy in Sarajevo will take place late this 
afternoon chaired by Greek Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias. 
The meeting will seek to form a unified stance by the 12 EU 
members to deal with the problem. The development of the 
discussion cannot be determined right now because most member 
countries have not made their positions public. Our 
correspondent reports that the only thing certain is that at 
least three countries, Germany, France, and Belgium, will ask 
the others to agree to harden the EU position. 

</TEXT>

