<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Liberal Party Decides To Reorganize </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0602221294 Rome RAI Uno Television Network in Italian 1900 
GMT 6 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0602221294 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome RAI Uno Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Italian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Liberal Party or a Federation of Liberals? A 
single secretary or an executive committee? For two days the 
Liberal Party has debated and argued these points, and a short 
time ago they made their decision. Mimmo Sacco reports. 
  [Sacco] Yes, now we can truly say goodbye to the old Italian 
Liberal Party [PLI]. The party has changed its image and moves 
are underway to turn it into a liberal federation. The decision 
was a bitter one. It was passed this evening by a show of 
hands. By the end of the vote there were signs of irritation 
and agitation -- easy to understand since the stakes were high. 
  The intervention of [PLI Secretary Raffaele] Costa was 
necessary to unblock the situation: An elected body will guide 
the party during this transitional period until the congress 
that is scheduled to take place mid-July. 
  The proposal put forward by De Luca -- that of direct 
elections for the secretary of the congress -- was rejected. De 
Luca himself had declared his intention of running for party 
secretary, and he loudly proclaimed that the party was being 
done away with. 
  As we have already said, the whole day was punctuated by 
long 
procedural matters, but the decision has now been made. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

