<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   France's Juppe: Karadzic Must Withdraw </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0702191494 Paris France-Inter Radio Network in French 1800 
GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0702191494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris France-Inter Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe by </F>
correspondent Quentin Dickinson in Brussels on 7 February -- 
recorded] 
  [Excerpt] [Passage omitted] Alain Juppe was not entirely 
satisfied with the outcome of the talks. He spoke to our 
reporter, Quentin Dickinson: 
  [Juppe] I would have liked the word ultimatum to figure in 
the communique, but so as not to be negative I would say that it 
is implied. It will be up to us in the North Atlantic Council 
to ensure that this resolution does not get bogged down and fade 
away. 
  [Dickinson] Do you believe Dr. Karadzic's statements to be 
purely tactical? 
  [Juppe] Well, we are used to so many statements, to so many 
meaningless cease-fires, that we cannot be satisfied with good 
intentions. It is true that Mr. Karadzic, probably realizing 
that the limits of horror were overstepped, is now speaking of 
demilitarizing Sarajevo. Well I tell him: You are on, do it. 
The best proof of his intentions would be to withdraw the heavy 
artillery around Sarajevo which is capable of shelling the city. 
If these artillery pieces are pulled back about 25 or 30 km, 
then what happened on Saturday in the Sarajevo market will no 
longer be possible. This would be far better proof of good 
intentions than a signature at the bottom of a document. So 
many signatures have proved worthless. 

</TEXT>

