<H3> <TI>   Portugal's Barroso: Communique `Condesending' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0702203494 Lisbon RTP Internacional Television in 
Portuguese 1900 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0702203494 </F>
<F P=104>  Lisbon RTP Internacional Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] The EU [European Union] has raised its voice and 
warned today that it is willing to use force to lift the siege 
on Sarajevo. The task, if carried out, will fall on NATO, which 
is to discuss air strikes at Wednesday's [9 February] meeting. 
Antonio Esteves Martins reports from Brussels. 
  [Martins] Following five hours of difficult discussions, the 
EU's only demand was an end to the siege on Sarajevo. The 
twelve foreign ministers, who do not rule out air strikes 
against Serb positions besieging Sarajevo, have left the final 
decision to the extraordinary meeting of the North Atlantic 
Council. This decision hardly hides the difficulties and the 
difference of opinion between the French, who advocate air 
strikes, and the British who oppose any type of military action. 
  [Begin recording] [Portuguese Foreign Minister Durao 
Barroso] 
The objective cannot be merely revenge, or punishment. It is a 
show of force resulting from our indignation at what appeared to 
us to be a highly condemnable act of violence. It is within 
this context that a decision will have to be taken in close 
consultation with our allies and bearing in mind, above all, the 
opinion of those who have soldiers and considerable forces on 
the ground. [end recording] 
  [Martins] In other words, an ultimatum was not issued today 
as the French wanted, but the use of force was not ruled out. 
Therefore, the message emerging from here could be seen by the 
Bosnian Serbs as a sign of weakness. 
  [Begin recording] [Barroso] We are conscious that this 
position may appear in some way condescending, but I should 
recall that we have always said that this conflict was not an 
easy one, and when a problem is not easy then there are no easy 
solutions either. [end recording] [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

