<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO To Meet To Discuss `Ultimatum' Over Sarajevo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0702144794 Paris AFP in English 1425 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0702144794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, Feb 7 (AFP) -- The North Atlantic Council 
will "very probably" meet on Tuesday [8 February] or Wednesday 
to discuss UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali's request 
for action over Sarajevo, the French Foreign Ministry said on 
Monday. 
  Deputy Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Catherine Colonna said a 
first informal meeting of the 16 members of the North Atlantic 
Treaty Organisation would be held on Monday to prepare the 
Council meeting. 
  France requested the meeting of NATO's governing body to 
discuss Butrus-Ghali's request that the alliance confirm its 
readiness to launch air strikes against artillery positions 
outside Sarajevo in the wake of Saturday's massacre of civilians. 
  Colonna said the convening of the Council would enable NATO 
to "announce precise, concrete measures" beyond a "simple 
reiteration" of measures the organisation has already adopted. 
  "France will ask the Atlantic Council to issue a clear 
ultimatum" on the lifting of the siege of Sarajevo and the 
"repositioning of Serb and Bosnian heavy artillery" in a radius 
of 30 kilometres (20 miles). 
  Colonna said the ultimatum should be "brief, precise and 
expressed in days." 
  Colonna added that Paris expected Monday's meeting in 
Brussels of the European Community foreign ministers to issue a 
"strong message" giving its full backing to France's efforts 
towards a NATO ultimatum. 

</TEXT>

