<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chretien: `Time to Weigh' Strike </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0702220894 Montreal Radio Canada International in English 
2130 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0702220894 </F>
<F P=104>  Montreal Radio Canada International </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Jean Chretien and other Canadian 
cabinet members say they want time to weigh options before 
deciding whether to support (?a) call for air strikes against 
Bosnian Serbs. 
  The call for the NATO-led strike was made by the UN 
secretary 
general, Butrus Butrus-Ghali, after 68 civilians were killed and 
almost 200 others were wounded in a mortar attack on a Sarajevo 
market place on Saturday [5 February]. 
  Mr. Chretien says Ottawa wants to consult its NATO allies 
and 
to obtain a report from Canadian peacekeepers in Bosnia, before 
reaching its decision. 
  A primary consideration for Ottawa is the safety of Canada's 
2,400 peacekeepers in the former Yugoslavia, but Mr. Chretien 
told the House of Commons that the situation in Bosnia is very, 
very bad, and that a decision may be taken in the next few days. 
  The United States and the European Union support the call by 
Mr. Butrus-Ghali, but Russia has signalled strong opposition to 
any attack. 

</TEXT>

