<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Belgium's Claes on Clash With Delcroix Over Air Strikes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0802172594 Brussels La Une Radio Network in French 1600 
GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0802172594 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels La Une Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] [Passage omitted] The Russian Foreign Ministry 
has accused the United Nations of overstepping its mandate by 
asking NATO if it would launch air strikes against Serb 
positions in Bosnia. These air strikes are also at the center 
of debate in Belgium. Defense Minister Leo Delcroix expressed 
reservations yesterday evening despite the fact that Foreign 
Minister Willy Claes was clearly in favor. Jean-Pierre 
Jacquemin interviewed the foreign minister: 
  [Begin recording] [Claes] I had several phone conversations 
during the weekend with the prime minister as well as with my 
colleague the defense minister. 
  [Jacquemin] Leo Delcroix has in fact expressed reservations 
regarding these air strikes. He justified his position by the 
presence in Bosnia of Belgian troops, who would be threatened if 
air strikes were launched. 
  [Claes] I understand that the defense minister is worried 
about the security of the peacekeeping troops. He is only doing 
his duty. But I am a bit puzzled by the warning given by some 
military experts. These air strikes were agreed upon by the UN 
Security Council more than a year ago. I suppose the military 
experts were asked to give their opinion at that time. 
  [Jacquemin] Are there any differences between you and Leo 
Delcroix within the government? 
  [Claes] No, I don't think so. The politician should 
sometimes make risky decisions. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

