<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   FRG Foreign, Defense Ministers on Air Strike Issue </TI></H3>
<H4>   Kinkel Urges Caution </H4>
<F P=102> LD0802220794 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 2020 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0802220794 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Erfurt, 8 Feb (DDP/ADN) -- Federal Foreign Minister 
Klaus Kinkel has urged Germany to remain cautious in considering 
air strikes against Serbian targets in Bosnia-Herzegovina. "As 
far as military deployment in the former Yugoslavia is 
concerned, we Germans are the worst advisers," Kinkel told the 
Erfurt THUERINGER ALLGEMEINE (Wednesday edition). One should 
await tomorrow's NATO session. Kinkel also appealed to the 
Social Democratic Party to give up its opposition to changing 
the Basic Law on the issue of out-of-area deployment of the 
Bundeswehr. Otherwise, he feared, "Germany would be harmed if 
we have to carry on behaving as we do now in such crises." 

</TEXT>

