<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Interior's Pasqua Threatens Troop Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0902124894 Paris France-Inter Radio Network in French 0720 
GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0902124894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris France-Inter Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Studio interview with Interior Minister Charles Pasqua by </F>
Annette Ardisson on 9 February -- live or recorded] 
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] [Ardisson] There is a NATO 
meeting today. Do you favor military intervention in 
Yugoslavia? Are we to wage war or not? 
  [Pasqua] What I think is that, if we continue to stay under 
the current conditions, we shall bear a responsiblity, not only 
[words indistinct], we already take great responsibility in 
what is happening -- but we shall also suffer dishonor. So, 
either NATO decides to intervene -- or else I don't see what we 
are still doing in Bosnia. There will be only one thing left to 
do, and that is to leave. I think that is what [Foreign 
Minister] Alain Juppe said last night: Everyone must be made to 
face up to their responsibilities. We cannot stand and watch 
with indifference what is happening, content ourselves with 
counting the dead, and say: Yes, well, Sunday wasn't very nice, 
there were 65 dead, 200 injured, children and so on; it's all 
very sad, but we cannot do anything about it. No, that isn't 
true. I think the time has come for everyone to face up to 
their responsibilities. 
  [Ardisson] What does that mean? 
  [Pasqua] It means.... 
  [Ardisson, interrupting] Does it mean: Let's go? 
  [Pasqua] It means we have to call on the Serbs to withdraw 
their artillery positions from around Sarajevo; if they do not, 
we have to intervene with air strikes. Otherwise, we should 
leave. 
  What's the point of it? We have already had 30 dead. We 
already have 30 French soldiers who have been killed, and we 
have had 300 wounded. And all of that for what? For nothing. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

