<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Balladur `Personally Asked for Ultimatum' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0902123894 Paris AFP in English 1219 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0902123894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, Feb 9 (AFP) -- France and the U.S. have set a 
10-day deadline for the Serbs to withdraw their artillery from 
Sarajevo or face air strikes, in a proposal being discussed 
Wednesday [9 February] by NATO envoys in Brussels, French 
officials said here. 
  French Prime Minister Edouard Balladur meanwhile told a 
cabinet meeting "he had personally asked for an ultimatum" to be 
given to the Serbs, government spokesman Nicolas Sarkozy said. 
  Balladur said he was following the situation with 
"particular 
vigilance" and that a "turning-point" had been reached over 
Bosnia, Sarkozy added. "Everyone must understand that nothing 
will be easy", Balladur was quoted as saying. 
  The French officials said the Franco-American proposal was 
that the Serbs withdraw or regroup their artillery, tanks and 
mortars outside a 20-kilometer (12 miles) radius of Sarajevo or 
face air strikes, the officials said. 
  They said the French and the Americans agreed on a joint 
proposal Tuesday evening after intense consultations among the 
allies that followed Saturday's killing of 68 people by a mortar 
shell in Sarajevo. 
  The French had proposed a 30 kilometer (18 miles) radius, 
but 
the two sides finally cut it to 20 kilometres, the officials 
said. However, an exception was made for a small area around 
Pale, seat of the Bosnian Serb parliament, on the heights above 
Sarajevo. 
  The proposal made no mention of regrouping Bosnian Moslem 
heavy weapons. 
  The officials said that after the 10-day deadline, all heavy 
weapons found in the exclusion area would be liable to 
destruction. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

