<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bosnia's Ljubijankic Meets With NATO's Balanzino </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0802160894 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1400 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0802160894 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bosnia-Herzegovina Foreign Minister Irfan 
Ljubijankic met with newly appointed acting NATO Secretary 
General Sergio Balanzino at NATO headquarters in Brussels. 
Bosnia-Herzegovina took advantage of the occasion to demand the 
immediate withdrawal of all heavy weapons positioned around 
Sarajevo to a point outside the town's range. If the Serbs do 
not do this within 48 hours, Minister Ljubijankic demanded air 
strikes. The credibility of NATO as a serious institution and 
[word indistinct] talks is at stake. 
  Our foreign minister repeated the demand to lift the arms 
embargo for Bosnia-Herzegovina. Ljubijankic and Balanzino 
discussed the military presence of the Croatian Army in our 
country. Our side referred to a secret agreement between Franjo 
Tudjman and Slobodan Milosevic on the division of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina between Croatia and Serbia. 
  Bosnia-Herzegovina expressed the desire to join the 
Partnership for Peace, an NATO initiative designed to unite with 
the former Socialist countries. Mr. Balanzino informed Minister 
Ljubijankic that NATO is keeping our country in mind but that 
the acceptance procedure is long, and the number of interested 
countries is great. 
  Mr. Balanzino informed the Bosnia-Herzegovina foreign 
minister that NATO has planned all the details for action in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina; only a political decision is needed. It is 
high time we preserve the meager credibility of the 
international community and NATO with resolute action. We 
seriously believe this, he emphasized. 

</TEXT>

