<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hungary, Ukraine Join NATO's Partnership for Peace </TI></H3>
<H4>   Says Partnership No `Substitute for Membership' </H4>
<F P=102> LD0802174694 Budapest Kossuth Radio Network in Hungarian 
1600 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0802174694 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Kossuth Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hungarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] According to the Hungarian foreign minister [Geza 
Jeszenszky], as a result of the Partnership for Peace program 
signed with NATO, Hungary's security has strengthened. 
Jeszenszky talked about this when he signed the document in 
Brussels. 
  However, the head of Hungarian diplomacy emphasized that the 
Partnership for Peace program could not substitute for full NATO 
membership. Speaking about the practical forms of cooperation, 
Jeszenszky said that joint planning and military exercises could 
be discussed. Moreover, it would be good to involve experts 
from the North Atlantic alliance in the Hungarian Army's 
modernization program. Jeszenszky, however, said that Hungary 
did not wish to participate in peacekeeping with large units. 

</TEXT>

