<H3> <TI>   Vranitzky Urges EU To Conclude Entry Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0802120894 Vienna DER STANDARD in German 8 Feb 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU0802120894 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna DER STANDARD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Vranitzky Appeals to All EU </F>
Government Heads"] 
  [Text] Vienna -- On Monday [7 February] Federal Chancellor 
Franz Vranitzky appealed to the heads of government of all 12 
member states of the European Union [EU] to do all they can to 
make sure that the entry negotiations are concluded according to 
plan. In a letter to the prime ministers, he also announced 
that he would contact them directly in the event the 
negotiations become difficult. 
  "The issues of transit, agriculture, and holiday homes 
remain 
unsolved. Austria's position on these issues has nothing to do 
with the wish to get special treatment, but it is the result of 
a businesslike effort to show the differences from other 
situations or to ask for a step-by-step adaptation to a joint 
system, which was conceded to other member states in the past, 
too," Vranitzky writes. 
  For the government it is, therefore, essential to reach a 
result in the negotiations that takes these special features 
into account. 

</TEXT>

