<F P=100> BENELUX </F>
<F P=101> Belgium </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dailies View Prospects for Air Strikes in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<H4>   U.S. Position May Win Over UK </H4>
<F P=102> BR0802160594 Brussels LA LIBRE BELGIQUE in French 8 Feb 94 p 
1 </F>

<F P=103> BR0802160594 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels LA LIBRE BELGIQUE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed Ch.Ly.: "Europe Asks For the Lifting of the </F>
Siege of Sarajevo -- The Means Will Be Defined on Wednesday by 
NATO. The Air Option Remains in the Air"] 
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] 
<H5>  American Support </H5>
  The position of the United States is also something to 
watch. 
Washington was in favor of the use of force eight months ago. 
Afterwards it changed its mind. And now it is once again in 
favor: On Monday [7 February] President Bill Clinton supported 
the request that NATO authorize air strikes against Serb 
batteries around Sarajevo. 
  U.S. Secretary of State Christopher Warren was very shocked 
by the carnage in Sarajevo. He seems to have won ground against 
some leading figures in the Pentagon who favor prudence. 
  It seems that a turnaround in U.S. policies would rally the 
United Kingdom to the air strike option. But account must be 
taken of Russia, for whom this option risks causing "an 
escalation in violence leading to the immediate withdrawal of UN 
forces." 

</TEXT>

