<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   AWACS To Stay in Event of Bosnia Air Strike </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0802230394 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 2140 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0802230394 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Halle (DDP/ADN) -- The German crew members on board 
the AWACS aircraft [over Bosnia] will not be pulled out in the 
event of NATO air strikes on Serbian targets. Tomorrow's 
Halle-based MITTELDEUTSCHE ZEITUNG reports German air force 
spokesman Lieutenant Colonel Eike Krueger as saying: "That is 
not planned at present." Apart from the ability to locate enemy 
aircraft movements and antiaircraft radar, and pass that 
information on to friendly aircraft, the AWACS planes can, 
according to information from the paper, provide close air 
support and reconnaisance. 
  Krueger said that in the event of NATO air strikes, AWACS 
would not be used to carry out such an operation. However, he 
admitted that the system would continue to be active in the same 
way in the event of air strikes, thus supplying information for 
the operation. The presence of a tactical air control 
organization on the ground was however decisive for successful 
air strikes. 
  The AWACS flights have been monitoring the no-fly zone over 
Bosnia declared by NATO since last April. 

</TEXT>

